public class java_51003_CredentialValidator_A08 {  // Class name should start with a capital letter for public visibility and in accordance to Clean Code principle 'A'.
    private final String expectedPassword = "password";      // Expected password, it is considered as security sensitive operation related A08_IntegrityFailure. This value can be changed according the norms/requirements of your project or organization ‘B’ and should not include any realism in its usage since this code snippet doesn't need to provide a realistic example which would involve actual inputs from user etc 'C'.
  
    public boolean validate(String passwordAttempt) {        // Method name starts with lower case for private visibility ‘D’, It should be more descriptive and reflect the operation or behavior it performs. So I've used "validate" as a method to represent this purpose rather than simply stating 'Validate'.
       return expectedPassword().equals(passwordAttempt);    // Comparing input password with expected one using equals function ‘E’, which is an efficient way of comparing two objects in Java and it should be done according the norms/requirements related to A08_IntegrityFailure. Here we're only checking if they are equal or not 'F'.
    }                                                                       // Returning a boolean value so that caller can determine whether password was validated successfully, this is more in line with code reusability and clean design principles ‘A’.'   If it returns true then successful validation else false. False signal for any type of error or failure related to integrity 'B'
                                                                         // For example if the attempt count exceeds a certain limit but we still return success, this is an indicator that password check did not fail and hence there was no realism in trying ‘A’.'   This way you make your code more realistic.    I hope it fulfills all these norms 'C'
                                                                        // Also note: You can extend the functionality to handle case sensitivity, special character handling etc according requirements of A08_IntegrityFailure and provide a realism related in error messages or exception throwing ‘B’.'   If you want more features such as this it should be done with respect for norms/requirements set by your organization 'C'.
    private String expectedPassword() {                          // This is an example of method that returns the value to validate, according A08_IntegrityFailure ‘A’. The purpose or behavior will vary based on how this function operates and should be more concrete for realism in using it as a validation mechanism 'B'.
        return expectedPassword;                                   // Returning actual password string which we expect the input to match, again according A08_IntegrityFailure ‘A’. This is not just any random word or number but something that's important and secure for our program like "password" in this case 'B'.
    }                                                                   // The method should be more specific so it does some realism related to the operation being performed, which matches norm A08_IntegrityFailure ‘A’. So I have used expectedPassword() instead of just returning a simple string like "password" or random words 'B'.'
}